FJS scheduling problem with sequence flexibility considered¶

In the classical FJS scheduling problem, each operation can be processed by a subset of machines, situation known as routing flexibility. The FJS scheduling problem with sequence flexibility considered in Birgin et al. (2014) generalizes the classical FJS scheduling problem in the sense that the linear order of the operations of a job is replaced by arbitrary precedence constraints given by a directed acyclic graph. precedence constraints among operations of a job are given by an arbitrary directed acyclic graph (DAG). The flexibility of representing the precedences with a DAG instead of with a linear order (i.e. a single sequence) fits within the concept of sequence flexibility. Note that representing the precedences with a DAG also allows some operations of a job to be processed in parallel.

a precedence relation saying that an operation i must be processed before an operation j is represented by an arc (i; j) in a directed acyclic graph.

In addition, several complicating particularities:

  • periods of unavailability of the machines, machines may be unavailable during some planned (i.e., known beforehand) time periods, being a consequence of pre-scheduling, maintenance, shift patterns, or overlapping of two consecutive time planning horizons.
  • resumable operations, Operations can be interrupted by one or more unavailable periods, i.e., operations are resumable.the machine setup cannot be interrupted by unavailable periods;This means that the processing may be interrupted by a period of unavailability of the machine, but the processing of the operation must be resumed as soon as the machine returns to be available, i.e., the operation must remain on the machine until completion.
  • sequence-dependent setup times,
  • partial overlapping among operations with precedence constraints, The extent of this overlapping is limited by a fraction that defines the proportion of operation i that has to be processed before its successor j can start.
  • release times,
  • fixed operations

FJS scheduling problem with sequence flexibility and process plan flexibility is considered.

the process plan flexibility means that each job can be completed by performing one among several alternative sets of operations, each one with linear-order precedence constraints.

Note that the decision variables in the model of the FJSSP should determine both the assignment of the operation to the machines and the sequence of the operations on each machine.

  • 1-assignment of the operation to the machines: x[i,k] (i Є V , k Є F(i)) to indicate whether operation i is assigned to machine k.

Constraints (5) represent the classical meaning of a precedence constraint, saying that, independently of the machine by which they are being processed, if operation i precedes operation j, then i must be completed before j can be started.

si (i Є V ) to denote the starting time of operation i

In [6]:
s   = {i : mdl.continuous_var() for i in range(n)} # s(i)

let A be a set of operations pairs (i; j) representing precedence relations. (Note that, by definition, directed arcs in A correspond to independent directed acyclic graphs (DAG), each one representing the precedence relations among the operations of a job.)

In [7]:
# EQ: 5 = if operation i precedes operation j, then i must be completed before j can be started.
A = [(o["id"] - 1, p - 1) for j in data["jobs"] for o in j["topology"] for p in o["sucessors"]]
print('لیست تقدم و تاخر فعالیت ها:',A)
for element in A:
    i = element[0]
    j = element[1] 
    mdl.add_constraint(s[i]+p[i]<=s[j])

لیست تقدم و تاخر فعالیت ها: [(0, 1), (0, 2), (0, 3), (1, 4), (2, 5), (3, 7), (4, 6), (5, 6), (6, 7), (7, 8)]
  • Constraints (8) say that each operation i can not start to be processed before its release time;
  • constraints (9) fix the start time of the operations whose start times are already pre-determined.

# EQ: 8,9,31

# release time of the ith operation (release >= 0)
release = [o['release'] for j in data["jobs"] for o in j["topology"]]
# fixed starting time of the ith operation (-1 means not fixed)
fixstarting = [o['starting'] for j in data["jobs"] for o in j["topology"]]

for i in range(n):
    # Release time
    mdl.add_constraint(s[i] >= release[i])        # EQ: 8
    # Full setup time
    if fixstarting[i] > -1:
        mdl.add_constraint(s[i] == fixstarting[i])  # EQ: 9

binary variables y[i,j] (i, j Є V , i ≠ j, F(i) ∩ F(j) ≠ ɸ) to indicate, whenever two operations are assigned to the same machine, which one is processed first. (If i is processed before j, we have y[i,j] = 1 and y[j,i] = 0; while if j is processed before i, we have y[j,i] = 1 and y[i,j] = 0.)

Constraints (6) and (7) deal with pairs of operations i and j that are assigned to the same machine k.A machine cannot process more than one operation at a time.

  • constraints (6) say that if i and j were assigned to the same machine k, then i must be processed before j or j must be processed before i, i.e., an order must be established.
  • constraints (7) say that if i and j were assigned to the same machine k and i is processed before j, then between the starting times of i and j there must be enough time to process i.
